===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|sise|sise, syse|regulation, control, limit|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|cise||lang=fro}}, {{term|sise||lang=fro}}, aphetism of ''[[assise]]'' "assize". Displaced native {{etyl|enm|-}} {{term|grete|grete, grette|size|lang=enm}} (from {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|grietu|grīetu, grȳtu|size, greatness|lang=ang}}).

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|obsolete|_|except|_|dialectal|lang=en}} An [[assize]]. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
#* '''1749''', Henry Fielding, ''Tom Jones'', Folio Society 1973, p. 560:
#*: I know you would have women above the law, but it is all a lye; I heard his lordship say at '''size''', that no one is above the law.
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} A regulation determining the [[amount]] of money paid in [[fees]], [[taxes]] etc. {{defdate|14th-18th c.}}
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} A fixed [[standard]] for the magnitude, quality, quantity etc. of goods, especially food and drink. {{defdate|15th-17th c.}}
